Diary of an epidemic: The birth of the barber

By Xiaoyu

The hairdresser arrived at 3pm after a two-week Journey. City freight and logistics began to recover, and since then, we've been receiving things at ever shorter intervals. The relationship between the community and volunteers spent a break-in period, to understand that she is not to take the opportunity to go out, the allocation of procurement rights to the community we call "tiger" lady. She does not mind the trouble, the detailed needs of each household statistics, the lead procurement, meet the leg is not convenient, ride the electric bike to send.

It was from her that we got hot and dry noodles, Tahini paste, Tarragon, emergency dog food. Hot and dry noodles in plastic bags, two catties, come back and take out a large stainless steel bowl, pour the noodles in one batch, then pull out the Tamarind from the pickle jar, dice, throw in the remaining red pepper, mix with the salt, sugar, soy sauce and sesame sauce, each person has a pair of chopsticks, and fish noodles out of the bowl. The last time we ate like this was in the'90s. The arrival of hot-and-dry noodles has raised hopes that the end of the epidemic is near.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A hospital nurse buys breakfast behind a barricade in a residential area of Wuhan. Photograph: Getty Images

"Tiger" in front of the door to form a temporary vegetable market, in the morning, people put their hands behind their backs, wearing masks, around the circle, procurement of necessary supplies. The community's centralized procurement, parallel existence, the supply of basic food and vegetables, and the distribution of what we call the "bear" lady, warm-hearted, outspoken, but careless mistakes. She wore gloves, made phone calls in the night wind, and shouted at someone to come down and get the food, or to return the wrong food. The two ladies of "the bear and the tiger" took care of the stomachs of the community. There are occasional surprises. The day there are live fish, we carry a plastic bucket, filled with water, back to four Mandarin fish and carp. In the sunny afternoon, my father scraped the fish scales, put a knife in his belly, pulled out his intestines, and put the fish in another bubble. Especially Watch out for the hidden spines in the Front Gills of the Mandarin Fish, who still scrapes his hand.

We kept the rest of the fish in barrels, covered them with sticks to keep them from jumping out. Into the cold basement at night to get things, bucket head up fish, round eyes, staring at you in the dark. Days after they were culled one by one, sharp eyes could still be felt in the basement. Another reason to be scared in the basement is that I think of the Old Lady crying in the Corner House. When walking, day or night, you can always hear her whining under the tree. Said she was sick, afraid of not seeing their children, and said that at home quarrel, but no one can go to find out, give comfort. Every time I put on my slippers and went to the basement, my father said quietly in the corridor, careful of the fish's eyes and strange sounds. He hasn't killed a fish or scared me in a long time.

The day the barber arrived, the father said, that night to cut. His hair was trimmed every day or twenty-five, and when it pricked his ears, he scratched them. It's been thirty-six nights now. My mother and I talked about who would do the cutting, and I said, cut the kid's hair, I'll do it. Father sat down on the stool and I put an apron on him.

Father: Don't you need a mirror in the front?

MOTHER: No, I'll stay here and keep an eye on everything.

Me: Let me try pushing a little less first.

Father: No, push it in a short time. If you hesitate too much, you won't get it done.

(I put the Caliper on, turned on the power, and buzzed. My father had so much white hair on his head that he couldn't tell it was short. I slowly pushed it around.)

Father: How did you get so much white hair cut.

Mother: You still think you are young.

Father: It could be shorter.

Me: I'll cut it down and brush it with my brush.

MOTHER: It's not even. You see, from above, there are three bumps.

Father: Kan? How did you manage the rice terraces?

With a movement of his head, he touched the Tush, and a piece of his scalp was visible at the temples of his left side

GRANDMA: It's over! It's over!

Mother: It's all right. If you have to, just flatten your head.

Father: Why did I listen to you two.

(I took my mother's advice and prepared to flatten my scalp with sideburns. Unexpectedly, two more scalp patches were visible on my left side.)

Me: Oh, no.

GRANDMA: I can't watch anymore. I'm going to my room.

Father: What, don't scare me. Take a picture for me.

(my mother laughed so hard that she couldn't stand up straight. She couldn't hold her mobile phone steady, so she took a picture with difficulty.)

Me: Don't show it to him now, I'm afraid I can't bear it. I'll fix it.

Father: (glances at the photo) Oh my God! (covers face and sighs)

Mother: You don't understand the structure of your father's head. You have to flatten it and push it up.

Me: Now you tell me?

Father (eyes straight, staring ahead) : How did I believe you two.

I put on the scissors and made do with it. Father went to take a shower, my mother and I just finished laughing. After a while, we heard a cry from the bathroom: Ah! Ah! What's going on here. Father rushed out, dripping water, the top of the head of the hair in different lengths, like the wind swept after the grass. I rubbed my aching belly with laughter, put on the scissors, and my father went back to the bathroom mirror. It's okay. I mean, hair is like a thesis. It's rewritten over and over. He bowed his head, and I took a comb and scissors, the top of the hair trim. The broken black and white hair, pitted against the smooth white sink, was all I could see. I saw my father's upper body in the mirror, a scar from an appendectomy on his right abdomen. I have a similar surgical scar on my upper body. I saw our bellies, and my father was waiting for me to weigh more than him, which was unthinkable until the outbreak made it possible. If I hadn't been sorting through my books and turned to a picture of my father in his 30s in front of Tiananmen Square, I would have forgotten how skinny he was and how thick his hair was. In fact, I was much closer to that picture than he is now. When did you get fat? I asked my father, blowing the hair clippings off the scissors. Right about now, he said, walking to the shower and showering a second time.

Over the next few days, I would touch his sideburns and the back of his head and say, that's not bad. Without looking up, he said, "I'll cut it for you. ". I said, "No, I'M GONNA go with long hair. ". My mother and my grandmother decided, unanimously, that they didn't need to trim their hair until it was unsealed. My father turned the work meeting into a voice conference. Their plan to go back to work was approved, and the string of preparations was busier than when he was at work. When I get up in the morning, before I go to bed at night, I hear him on the phone in my bedroom. It was the same as when he left early and came home late. I would get up in the morning of winter and summer vacation, have a family meal like this, and then I would see him go out, footsteps from heavy to light disappear in the stairwell. When he came home, he opened the door and asked, where is he? He used to say that to his grandson during the outbreak, which made me think it was a new habit. Now that I think about it, 20 years ago, he would say to the kids in the room, "where is he? ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A temporary roadblock has been erected in a residential community in Wuhan. Photograph: Getty Images

The pass was done, and he was back on the job the next morning. I have to go to work tomorrow, he said at the dinner table. At least there won't be traffic, we said. My mother and I hid on the balcony, reading, listening to his voice on the phone in the living room through the wall. He must have forgotten to drink the water again, and asked him to boil it, his mother said. We went to see that the water in the kettle was really cold. Mother said, finally ask you to serve the masses for a time, false, are false. My father said, my hair is like this, but also let me serve, and let me boil water.

The next day, at dawn, I woke up and went back to sleep. When I got up again, the room was quiet and there was no phone call. I went to the kitchen and there was a used bowl and a pair of chopsticks on the table. Grandma said she just went downstairs. I threw on my slippers and went downstairs, my car out of its parking space. I then chase out a few steps, also disappeared, but saw the mother back hand on the road. I said, what are you going to do. She turned around and said, "go to the tiger" to see the food. I said, I'll come with you. She said, "well, why aren't you wearing a mask? ". I'm in a hurry, I said.

Not only does the epidemic have a profound impact on our lives today, it will also occupy our memories and change our minds for a long time to come. We need more eyes to continue to observe and document the crises and changes of our time. These are sincere and weighty records, and we will keep them.
